**The Last Lightkeeper**  

On a tiny, windswept island at the edge of the world, an old lighthouse stood stubbornly against the crashing waves. Its keeper, Elias, had lived there alone for forty years, tending the light that guided lost ships home.  

One stormy night, as Elias wound the clockwork mechanism that kept the beacon turning, he heard a knock at the door—a sound he hadn’t heard in decades. When he opened it, a drenched young woman stood there, clutching a rusted lantern.  

"I found this washed ashore," she said, shivering. "It has your name carved into it."  

Elias’s hands trembled as he took it. The lantern was his father’s, lost at sea the night Elias became the keeper.  

"How?" he whispered.  

The woman smiled sadly. "The lighthouse calls things back—lost ships, lost souls. Even memories."  

As the storm raged outside, Elias realized why he’d never left. The island wasn’t just keeping sailors safe—it was keeping *him* from drifting away.  

By dawn, the woman was gone. But the lantern sat on the windowsill, its flame burning steady, as if it had never gone out.
